<frame name="FR_Agree_or_refuse_to_act" ID="10002" xsi:schemaLocation="../schema/frame.xsd" xmlns="http://framenet.icsi.berkeley.edu" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" domains="Cognitive_positions,Verbal_communication">
    <definition>&lt;def-root&gt;A &lt;fen&gt;Cognizer&lt;/fen&gt; either agrees to or refuses to engage in a &lt;fen&gt;Proposed_action&lt;/fen&gt;. He either thinks this agreement/refusal or communicates it to an interlocutor who might or might not be the person who proposed the &lt;fen&gt;Proposed_action&lt;/fen&gt; (note though that neither the addressee nor the proposer can be realized locally).

&lt;ex&gt;&lt;/ex&gt;
&lt;asf&gt;Distinctions with other frames&lt;/asf&gt;:
&lt;ex&gt;&lt;/ex&gt;

≠ &lt;frframe&gt;Willingness&lt;/frframe&gt;: in the Willingness frame, the Cognizer would engage in an Activity if prompted to do so, whereas FR_Agree_or_refuse_to_act is the situation in which the Cognizer communicates their willingness to engage in a Proposed_action.

        &lt;ex&gt;&lt;/ex&gt;
&lt;asf&gt;Relation to fndata-1.5&lt;/asf&gt; : corresponds to Agree_or_refuse_to_act, in which the Interlocutor is no longer a Core frame element (although it can be conceptually present) since no LUs in that frame subcategorize for it. Also, the Interlocutor and the entity who proposed the &lt;fen&gt;Proposed_action&lt;/fen&gt; could be different. Finally, the agreement/refusal could theoretically be purely interior, not communicated (as in "I think he refuses to mourn").
        &lt;ex&gt;&lt;/ex&gt;

&lt;/def-root&gt;</definition>
